Peter Boneparth, who resigned Thursday as chief executive, president and a director of Jones Apparel, spent much of his six years at the company diversifying its clothing offerings, including buying Barneys.

Credit
            Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times        



Peter Boneparth, the aggressive deal-making chief executive of the Jones Apparel Group,  which owns brands like Anne Klein, Jones New York and Nine West, stepped down yesterday.Jones promoted its chief financial officer, Wesley R. Card, to succeed Mr. Boneparth.Jones did not conduct a search for a new chief executive, people briefed on the change said, indicating to some analysts that the board still intended to sell the company.Jones has been shopped to private equity firms and other potential buyers for more than a year, but no bidder has emerged with a high enough offer for the entire company.Last month, Jones agreed to sell a division, Barneys New York, for about $825 million to Istithmar, the investment arm of the Dubai government. Fast Retailing, a Japanese retail company, has since offered $900 million for Barneys. The contractual terms of the Barneys deal with Istithmar allow Jones to continue considering offers for Barneys and  for the entire company until that deal closes.

